      "content": "That is a very common argument supported by economic studies, but its impact varies significantly depending on local purchasing power. In low-cost rural areas, the newly paid workers might already have sufficient disposable income, meaning the local multiplier effect could be limited compared to a scene of poverty where every extra dollar significantly boosts their spending. Additionally, while some workers do spend locally, many still spend on major needs or outside the community, which can dilute the direct economic boost for exactly the type of small businesses seeking low operating costs.",
