      "content": "While the laws are fundamentally fair to workers by improving living standards, they often create an uneven playing field where large chains absorb costs more easily than small, cash-strapped new businesses. In rural areas with narrow profit margins, these regulations can indeed lead to the growth and closure of existing small enterprises, potentially increasing the local dominance of big franchise brands. Ultimately, the trade-off shifts the economic benefits from small shop owners to a workforce that previously lacked basic financial security.",
